## Word Order ##
################

# Minimally a predicate. Phrases typically contain auxiliaries, which
# can express time, motion and location, among other things.
# Objects are overtly stated after the predicate and subject, although
# transitivity is expressed through suffixation (TR).

# Note: The auxiliary niʔ expresses distance from the speaker
# and is being glossed as 'there' for our purposes. Although
# its meaning is spatial, it is most often translated as
# the past tense, and we have followed in this tradition. ʔi is 
# complementary to niʔ, denoting 'here' (spacial proximity
# to the speaker) and sometimes 'now'. Translations of this
# auxiliary are not consistent, so for now we are simply
# showcasing its position in the utterance and not attempting 
# an analysis of its English counterpart.



