###########
## Tense ##
###########

# Halkomelem makes a distinction between past, present
# and future. Present in the plain verb, while past 
# and future are indicated with suffixes. The analysis
# in (Suttles 2004) treats the future marker as a 
# particle since its distribution is relatively free
# after the main verb, however this is not compatible with our 
# current grammar so we are treating it as a suffix
# binding to the personal affixes.

# The past tense suffix -əɬ generally occurs after the transitive, object,
# and agreement suffixes and before the personal suffixes. Without
# the auxiliary niʔ ('there'), it can denote an incipient past, 
# that is, intention from the perspective of the past. When niʔ is
# present, -əɬ will almost always attach to it, however its location
# is fairly fluid and it can follow words of any type, even more
# multiple words in the same sentence, although this is not common.
# We will seek to establish the freedom of -əɬ in later labs, when
# the rest of the grammar is more fleshed out. 

# The future suffix -ceʔ follows the personal suffixes. We have no
# data to back up a theory that the two are mutually incompatible,
# however logic would declare that this is so and we have found
# no examples to contradict this. Thus their co-occurrence is
# prevented in our grammar. 

